DC Recreation Centers (Fitness Facilities)¶

Today I learned of the fitness facilities that are run by the District. There is a pretty low annual fee of $125, and apparently that gets you access to all facilities in the city. I already knew about the one close to my office, but naturally I wondered about how convenient other locations would be. Sure, I could have gone the Google Maps route, but where's the fun in that?

Let's make something that looks cooler. Besides, I could certainly use the practice and I am not entirely sure how to feed Google Maps a vector of locations anyway. First, let's enable R and read in the data (which I cleanly copied from the DPR website and pasted into a .csv).

#Enable R capability

As can be seen, we have only addresses for location. This can easily be fixed by Google's geocoding API (which is embedded in the ggmap package).

In [26]: 
%%R
#Geocode coordinates
coords<-geocode(as.character(r$Address))

#Split matrix into long/lat, and attach to the data.frame
r$lon<-coords[,1]
r$lat<-coords[,2]

#Verify success
print(r)

Just like that, we have enough to plot. Note that I am centering the map on my house to identify what is convenient for me. Screw anyone else who needs this info...

In [32]: 
%%R -w 1000 -h 1000

#Generate map tile, upon which we will plot our data
dc_map<-qmap('22 Bryant St. NE Washington DC',zoom=14,maptype = 98997,api_key='439cf1240ef4468ebb4277d0d31a6570',source = "cloudmade")

#Plot rec center locations, colored by Ward
print(dc_map + geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat,colour = as.character(Ward)),size=10,data = r))
